<DOC><DOCNO> AP890219-0012 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-19-89 2348EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Networks-Japan     02-19 0342</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Networks-Japan,0352</SECOND><HEAD>CBS Blitzes Other Networks With Massive Far East Trip</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD><BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   CBS is blitzing the other networks' coverage ofEmperor Hirohito's funeral and President Bush's trip to the Far Eastthis week, taking most of its news broadcasts to Japan at a cost ofat least $2 million.   ABC, NBC and CNN also will be on location for Hirohito's funeral.Bush will attend the funeral Thursday in Tokyo, then he goes toChina and Korea.   At a news conference last week, ``Evening News'' anchor DanRather called the coverage ``unprecedented'' by broadcast news, butwarranted by Hirohito's death as a symbol of ``the end of thepostwar era.''   ABC's Peter Jennings will anchor ``ABC World News Tonight'' fromTokyo all week. NBC's Tom Brokaw will anchor ``NBC Nightly News''from Tokyo on Thursday and Friday, then from Beijing on Saturday andSunday. CNN's Bernard Shaw and Mary Alice Williams will anchor livecoverage of the funeral from Tokyo.   The networks have all focused on Japan's culture and economy inreports leading up to the funeral and Bush's trip.   CBS, which began on-location coverage Sunday with ``CBS SundayMorning,'' also is taking the ``CBS Evening News,'' ``CBS ThisMorning,'' ``48 Hours'' and ``Face the Nation'' to Japan. Thecoverage concludes next Sunday with ``Face the Nation'' from Beijing.   The broadcasts will focus on Japan's relationship to the UnitedStates in terms of economy, lifestyles and military interdependence.   CBS' ``48 Hours'' will have live coverage of the beginning of thefuneral Thursday night, when it will be Friday morning in Japan.   CBS News figures it will have 18 hours of special coverage fromthe Far East at a cost of at least $2 million, Rather said.   ``We thought long and hard about whether should make this kind ofcommitment to this story at this time,'' he said. ``This is a gamblefor us.''   ``But we think in this particular case we can make it work,'' hesaid.</TEXT></DOC>